---
/** Personal finance: the cost of waiting to invest. */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import ProcrastinationCalculator from '../../components/calculators/ProcrastinationCalculator.tsx';
import { procrastinationCost } from '../../lib/personal-finance';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const ex = procrastinationCost(500, 0.07, 30, 5);
---

<Base
  title="Cost of waiting to invest calculator 2026"
  description="What waiting to invest costs by retirement — a few years' delay can cost more than the skipped contributions, because early years compound longest."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">Personal finance</p>
    <h1>The cost of waiting to invest</h1>
    <p class="tagline">The most expensive investing mistake isn’t a bad pick — it’s a late start. See what a few years’ delay quietly costs by the time you need the money.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    Compounding rewards time more than amount. The dollars you invest earliest have the longest to grow, so
    delaying even a few years can cost more than all the contributions you skipped — because you lose the growth
    those early dollars would have thrown off for decades.
  </p>

  <ProcrastinationCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked example</h2>
  <p>Investing {formatMoney(500)}/month at 7%, with 30 years until you need it — starting now versus waiting 5 years:</p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Scenario</th><th>Ends with</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Start now (30 years)</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.ifStartNow)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Wait 5 years (25 years)</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.ifDelayed)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cost of the 5-year delay</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.costOfWaiting)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Extra contributions from starting now</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.contributedNow - ex.contributedDelayed)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    Waiting five years costs {formatMoney(ex.costOfWaiting)} — far more than the
    {' '}{formatMoney(ex.contributedNow - ex.contributedDelayed)} of extra contributions those five years would
    have added. The gap is lost compounding: the early dollars had the longest runway, and you gave it up.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Why is the cost bigger than the missed contributions?</h3>
    <p>Because the dollars you skip early are the ones that would have compounded the longest. Five years of
      {formatMoney(500)}/month is {formatMoney(ex.contributedNow - ex.contributedDelayed)} of contributions, but
      the growth those dollars would have earned over the full horizon is worth much more.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Is it ever too late to start?</h3>
    <p>No — the cost of waiting is exactly why the best time to start is now rather than later still. A shorter
      runway means less compounding, but every year you delay only makes the next start more expensive.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/fire-calculator/">FIRE calculator</a> — how the head start shortens your timeline</li>
    <li><a href="/self-employed-retirement-calculator/">Self-employed retirement</a> — tax-advantaged places to start</li>
    <li><a href="/net-worth-calculator/">Net worth</a> — track the result</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">Assumes a steady annual return, which markets do not deliver smoothly. An illustration, not a promise. Not financial advice.</p>
</Base>
